images.alt:
Two dog-dragon hybrids face each other in profile: a blue one on the left and an orange-red one on the right. Wings folded, golden eyes steady, they meet nose-to-nose across a narrow gap against a moody, textured sky—cool vs. warm contrast.

Long description:
A high-detail digital illustration shows two mythic, canine-featured dragons in a symmetrical, side-by-side composition. The left creature is rendered in deep slate-blue tones; the right is saturated orange-red. Both are shown from the shoulders up in strict profile, facing each other with noses nearly touching, separated by a slim vertical band of background. Their expressions are calm and intent, golden irises catching the light.

Each creature blends dog anatomy with draconic traits. Muzzles are canine, with soft whisker pads and black noses. The blue creature has tall, upright, pointed ears and layered, scale-like feathers that cascade down the neck and shoulder. The orange-red creature’s silhouette is rounder, with small horn nubs or backward-swept ridges above the brow and denser, plate-like scales that read as overlapping feathers along the neck. Both have leathery, batlike wings tucked behind them; the wing fingers and membranes are visible as dark arcs framing the shoulders.

Linework is inky and precise with varied weight, emphasizing fur texture, scale edges, and the contours of the snouts. Lighting is cinematic: subtle rim light defines the outer edges, while gentle inner glow brings out micro-contrast in the feathers/scales. The palette is deliberately split—cool blue on the left, warm red/orange on the right—creating a complementary color standoff.
The background is a stormy, grain-textured gradient: desaturated teal above shading to muted tan near the bottom, with faint diagonal streaks suggesting rain or wind. No text or additional objects appear. The overall mood is poised and intimate, like a face-off or wordless understanding between equals.

record.text: A 10″ Telescope, Because You Only Live Once https://hackaday.com/2025/09/16/a-10-telescope-because-you-only-live-once/ #telescopemirror #mirrorgrinding #classichacks #telescope #Space #YOLO

external.description:
Why build a telescope? YOLO, as the kids say. Having decided that, one must decide what type of far-seer one will construct. For his 10″ reflector, [Carl Anderson] once again said “Yolo”— this time not as a slogan, but in reference to a little-known type of reflecting telescope.

Telescope or sci-fi laser gun? YOLO, just try it.

The Yolo-pattern telescope was proposed by [Art Leonard] back in the 1960s, and was apparently named for a county in California. It differs from the standard Newtonian reflector in that it uses two concave spherical mirrors of very long radius to produce a light path with no obstructions. (This differs from the similar Schiefspiegler that uses a convex secondary.) The Yolo never caught on, in part because of the need to stretch the primary mirror in a warping rig to correct for coma and astigmatism.

[Carl] doesn’t bother with that, instead using modern techniques to precisely calculate and grind the required toric profile into the mirror. Grinding and polishing was done on motorized jigs [Carl] built, save for the very final polishing. (A quick demo video of the polishing machine is embedded below.)

The body of the telescope is a wooden truss, sheathed in plywood. Three-point mirror mounts alowed for the final adjustment. [Carl] seems to prefer observing by eye to astrophotography, as there are no photos through the telescope. Of course, an astrophotographer probably would not have built an F/15 (yes, fifteen) telescope to begin with. The view through the eyepiece on the rear end must be astounding.

If you’re inspired to spend your one life scratch-building a telescope, but want something more conventional, check out this comprehensive guide. You can go bit more modern with 3D printed parts, but you probably don’t want to try spin-casting resin mirrors. Or maybe you do: YOLO!
external.title: A 10″ Telescope, Because You Only Live Once
